__data__.text: american revolution: the american revolution was an ideological and political movement in the thirteen colonies that led to the american revolutionary war and the establishment of the united states of america
thirteen colonies: the thirteen colonies were the british colonies in north america that played a significant role in the american revolution
british america: british america refers to the territories in north america under british rule during the american revolution
american revolutionary war: the american revolutionary war was a conflict between the thirteen colonies and great britain  culminating in american independence
battles of lexington and concord: the battles of lexington and concord marked the beginning of the american revolutionary war on april 19  1775
leaders of the american revolution: leaders of the american revolution were colonial separatist figures who advocated for independence from britain and played key roles in the war

second continental congress: the second continental congress represented the colonies and played a crucial role in the revolutionary war  appointing george washington and adopting the declaration of independence
independence hall: independence hall in philadelphia was the location where the second continental congress convened and adopted the declaration of independence
continental army: the continental army was formed by the second continental congress and led by george washington during the revolutionary war
george washington: george washington was appointed as the commander in chief of the continental army and played a pivotal role in the american revolution
declaration of independence: the declaration of independence was adopted by the second continental congress in 1776  declaring the colonies  independence from britain
siege of yorktown: the siege of yorktown in 1781 was a decisive victory for the continental army led by george washington  leading to british acknowledgment of american independence
king george iii: king george iii of britain played a significant role in the events leading to the treaty of paris and the recognition of american independence
treaty of paris: the treaty of paris in 1783 formally ended the american revolutionary war and recognized the independence of the united states
united states of america: the united states of america was established as a sovereign nation following the american revolution and the treaty of paris
british parliament: british parliament played a key role in imposing taxes and passing acts that led to tensions with the american colonies
stamp act congress: the stamp act congress in 1765 protested against taxation without representation  highlighting colonial grievances against british policies
townshend acts: the townshend acts of 1767 heightened tensions between the colonies and britain by imposing new taxes and regulations
boston massacre: the boston massacre in 1770 involved british troops killing protesters in boston  escalating tensions in the colonies
gaspee affair: the gaspee affair in 1772 involved the destruction of a british customs ship by anti tax demonstrators  symbolizing resistance to british authority
boston tea party: the boston tea party in 1773 was a protest against british taxation policies  leading to the dumping of tea into boston harbor by american colonists
sons of liberty: the sons of liberty were activists who protested against british policies  notably organizing the boston tea party
lee resolution: the lee resolution of 1776 declared the colonies  support for independence  paving the way for the adoption of the declaration of independence
articles of confederation: the articles of confederation were debated in the second continental congress as an early attempt to establish a system of self governance for the colonies
thomas jefferson: thomas jefferson played a significant role in drafting the declaration of independence  embodying key political philosophies of the revolution
marquis de lafayette: marquis de lafayette supported the continental army during the revolutionary war  contributing to the victory at yorktown
charles cornwallis: charles cornwallis was a british general who surrendered at the siege of yorktown  marking a turning point in the revolutionary war
loyalists: loyalists were individuals who remained loyal to the british crown during the american revolution  leading to their migration after the war
constitutional republic: the united states became the first constitutional republic founded on principles of consent of the governed and the rule of law after the revolution
capt  levi preston: capt  levi preston is a colonist from danvers  massachusetts  who expressed the sentiment of self governance and rebellion against england
charles ii: charles ii is a historical figure who faced opposition from the massachusetts colony and was not immediately recognized as king after his coronation
james ii: james ii  brother of charles ii  attempted to bring new england under direct english control  facing fierce opposition from the colonists
edmund andros: edmund andros was appointed royal governor of the dominion of new england  imposing direct rule and facing resentment from the colonists
new england colonies: the new england colonies were part of the dominion of new england and played a significant role in the resistance against english control
dominion of new england: the dominion of new england was a political entity created by james ii to consolidate control over new england  facing strong opposition from the colonists
glorious revolution of 1688: the glorious revolution of 1688 marked the removal of james ii from power and the restoration of colonial self governance
boston revolt: the 1689 boston revolt overthrew dominion rule in new england  leading to the reassertion of colonial governments
william and mary: william and mary were the monarchs who granted new charters to the new england colonies after the glorious revolution  restoring local self government
british government: the british government fielded soldiers and contributed to the war effort during the french and indian war
french: france s territory east of the mississippi river was acquired by great britain after defeating france
bute ministry: the bute ministry decided to garrison soldiers in north america  impacting the military presence in the region
british army: british army officers were allowed to remain on active duty with full pay in north america  influencing the military strategy
native americans: native americans were involved in conflicts with white colonists and british soldiers in newly acquired territories
pontiac s war: pontiac s war was launched by native americans in response to increased migration beyond the appalachian mountains
grenville ministry: the grenville ministry issued the royal proclamation of 1763  affecting territorial designations and settlement policies
french and indian war: the french and indian war involved british regulars  colonial volunteers  and significant spending on the war effort
colonies: the colonies contributed money to the war effort during the french and indian war  with partial reimbursement by the british government
great britain: great britain defeated france during the french and indian war and acquired french territory east of the mississippi river
north america: the decision to garrison soldiers in north america was made by the bute ministry  impacting military presence in the region
appalachian mountains: migration beyond the appalachian mountains increased after the french threat was removed  leading to conflicts with native americans
royal proclamation of 1763: the royal proclamation of 1763 designated territories closed to white settlement  affecting westward migration and angering settlers
french revolution: the french revolution was a period of political and societal change in france  marked by significant events such as the estates general of 1789 and the coup of 18 brumaire in 1799

estates general: the estates general is a representative body last convened in 1614  proposed to approve new taxes<SEP>the estates general is proposed to approve new tax laws  with representation from the clergy  nobility  and third estate<SEP>the estates general of 1789 was a crucial event that marked the beginning of the french revolution  leading to the formation of the national assembly
coup of 18 brumaire: the coup of 18 brumaire on 9 november 1799 marked the end of the french revolution and the establishment of the consulate under napoleon bonaparte
ancien r gime: the ancien r gime refers to the old regime in france  characterized by social  political  and economic factors that contributed to the revolution
louis xvi: louis xvi was the king of france during the french revolution  whose attempted flight to varennes and subsequent execution were significant events
national assembly: the national assembly was formed by the representatives of the third estate during the french revolution  leading to radical measures and the abolition of feudalism
storming of the bastille: the storming of the bastille on 14 july was a pivotal event in the french revolution  symbolizing the people s uprising against the monarchy
reign of terror: the reign of terror was a period of mass executions and political repression during the french revolution  led by the radical jacobins
thermidorian reaction: the thermidorian reaction marked the end of the reign of terror in july 1794  leading to a shift in power away from the radical jacobins
tax farmers: tax farmers are contracted to collect taxes  keeping a portion as personal profit
nobility: nobility benefits from exemptions  leading to a heavier tax burden on peasants
church: church also benefits from exemptions  contributing to the tax burden on peasants
peasants: peasants bear the main tax burden due to exemptions enjoyed by the nobility and church
france: france is the primary funder of the anglo french war of 1778 1783 and faces a debt crisis by 1788
calonne: calonne proposes tax reforms and faces rejection by the nobility and parlements
brienne: brienne submits new taxes for approval  facing rejection by the nobility and parlements
crown: the crown engages in a conflict with the parlements over tax reforms  leading to a national crisis
parlements: parlements oppose new taxes  arguing for approval by the estates general and defending national rights
public opinion: public opinion supports the parlements in the conflict over tax reforms  leading to riots
jacques necker: jacques necker replaces brienne as the french finance minister during the crisis
society of thirty: society of thirty campaigns for increased third estate representation and individual voting rights
abb  siey s: abb  siey s issues influential pamphlets advocating for the third estate s representation and role as a national assembly
jean joseph mounier: jean joseph mounier organizes regional meetings and petitions in support of increased third estate representation
antoine barnave: antoine barnave supports demands for increased third estate representation through activism
maximilien robespierre: maximilien robespierre supports demands for increased third estate representation through activism
tax laws: tax laws need to be registered with regional judicial bodies or parlements  which can block them  making reform difficult
anglo french war of 1778 1783: the war was primarily funded by france through loans  leading to financial strain post war
debt crisis: france faces a debt crisis by 1788  with a significant portion of state revenue allocated to debt servicing
assembly of notables: the assembly of notables  dominated by the nobility  rejects new tax proposals  advocating for approval by the estates general
regional judicial bodies: regional judicial bodies play a role in approving new tax laws  affecting the reform process
national crisis: the conflict between the crown and the parlements escalates into a national crisis  with public opinion supporting the parlements
censorship: censorship restrictions are relaxed  leading to increased political discourse and publication of pamphlets
political clubs: political clubs play a role in the political activism and discourse surrounding tax reforms and representation
public debate: the public debate intensifies with the publication of numerous political pamphlets  advocating for various positions
representation: the issue of representation  particularly for the third estate  becomes a central point of contention and debate
counting votes: the method of counting votes for the estates general becomes a significant issue  impacting the balance of power between the estates
doubling representation: the demand for doubling third estate representation gains momentum  leading to political activism and support
individual voting: calls for individual voting rights become prominent in the discourse surrounding representation and political participation
economic impact: the economic growth does not translate proportionally to tax revenue  impacting the financial stability of the state
tax exemptions: exemptions enjoyed by the nobility and church contribute to the heavier tax burden on peasants
new taxes: proposed new taxes face rejection by various bodies  leading to a financial and political crisis
financial reforms: proposed financial reforms  including a universal land tax  face resistance from the nobility and parlements
political pamphlets: political pamphlets play a crucial role in disseminating ideas and shaping public opinion during the crisis
regional meetings: regional meetings are organized to garner support for increased third estate representation and political reforms
petitions: petitions are circulated to advocate for political reforms and increased representation for the third estate
literature: literature  including pamphlets and writings  is used to convey political ideas and mobilize support for reforms
